      "A transit occurs when a planet crosses the face of its star as seen from Earth, blocking a tiny fraction of starlight — often parts per thousand for a Jupiter-sized world and parts per hundred thousand for an Earth-sized planet around a Sun-like star. The dip’s depth constrains the planet-to-star radius ratio; the repeat period gives the orbital period; careful modeling of ingress and egress encodes impact parameter and mean stellar density. NASA’s Kepler mission monitored more than 150,000 stars for years with space-based photometric stability, enabling the first robust statistical census of small planets. TESS surveys nearly the whole sky, prioritizing bright, nearby hosts suitable for mass measurement and atmospheric follow-up.",
