    headline: "Earth’s Magnetic Field Is a Self-Sustaining Dynamo — Recorded in Rocks and Space",
    summary: "Convective motion of liquid iron in the outer core generates the geomagnetic field. Paleomagnetism records polarity reversals; the magnetosphere shields the atmosphere from solar wind.",
    ref: "IGRF · paleomagnetism · magnetospheric physics",
    anchorVerse: { verse: "Job 26:7", text: "He stretches out the north over the void and hangs the earth on nothing." },
    body: [
      "Earth’s magnetic field is not a permanent bar magnet frozen in rock. It is continually regenerated by a geodynamo: convective motion of liquid iron alloy in the outer core, influenced by Earth’s rotation (Coriolis forces), latent heat and light-element release at the inner-core boundary, and electrical conductivity. Moving conductor plus seed field induces currents that sustain and reshape the field — a self-exciting dynamo.",
      "At the surface, the field is largely dipolar, with poles offset from the geographic poles and a strength of order tens of microteslas. Spherical harmonic models such as the International Geomagnetic Reference Field (IGRF) capture the main field and its secular variation. Higher multipoles and crustal magnetic anomalies add structure important for navigation and geology.",
      "Paleomagnetism extends the record into deep time. When igneous rocks cool through the Curie temperature, magnetic minerals lock in the ambient field direction and polarity. Sedimentary rocks can also acquire remanence. The resulting polarity timescale shows that the field has reversed many times — irregularly, not on a simple clock — with transition periods that are geologically brief compared with chrons of stable polarity.",
      "Secular variation is visible within a human lifetime: declination and inclination drift; intensity has declined in recent centuries in some global metrics; the South Atlantic Anomaly is a region of weaker field monitored carefully for satellite radiation exposure. ESA’s Swarm constellation and ground observatories keep the living map up to date.",
      "Above the atmosphere, the geomagnetic field carves the magnetosphere — a cavity in the solar wind bounded by the magnetopause. The bow shock stands upstream; Van Allen radiation belts trap energetic particles; magnetic reconnection at the magnetopause and in the magnetotail drives storms and substorms. This space-plasma environment is measured by fleets of spacecraft and is the stage on which auroras form.",
      "Comparative planetology clarifies why Earth’s dynamo matters. Mars lacks a global dynamo today and shows evidence of greater atmospheric loss; Venus has no strong internal field despite a similar size. Magnetic shielding is not the only factor in atmospheric retention, but it is part of Earth’s long-term habitability architecture.",
      "Numerical dynamo simulations in rotating spherical shells reproduce dipole-dominated fields, westward drift features, and spontaneous polarity reversals under certain parameters. They link observable surface field behavior to deep fluid dynamics we cannot drill into — theory constrained by seismology of the core and by the magnetic record.",
      "Practical consequences range from compass navigation and animal magnetoreception research to induced currents in power grids during geomagnetic storms. The field is both a scientific probe of Earth’s deep interior and an operational space-weather parameter.",
      "An invisible architecture — written in molten iron and planetary spin — orders phenomena from the compass needle to the polar aurora. It is creation’s hidden scaffolding, made visible by magnetometers, rocks, and satellites.",
    ],
